<mjml>
  <mj-head>
    <mj-style> h2,img,p { margin:0; } td{ padding-top:0 !important; } p {margin-bottom: 10px;}</mj-style>
    <!-- <mj-font name="Roboto" href="https://fonts.googleapis.com/css?family=Roboto" /> -->
    <mj-font name="Roboto+Serif" href="https://fonts.googleapis.com/css2?family=Roboto+Serif:ital,opsz,wght@0,8..144,100..900;1,8..144,100..900&display=swap" />
  </mj-head>
  <mj-body background-color="#f0f1f3">

    <mj-spacer height="15px"></mj-spacer>
    
    <!-- Logo Header -->
    <mj-section background-color="#ffffff">
      <mj-spacer height="10px" />
      <mj-column padding="10px 12px 10px 12px" width="100%">
        <mj-spacer height="16px" />
        <mj-image padding="10px 12px" css-class="light_img" width="150px" src="https://www.businesshistory.co/logo-gray.png" href="https://www.businesshistory.co" alt="" />
       
        
        <mj-divider border-width="1px" border-style="solid" border-color="lightgrey" padding="10px 0px" />
        <mj-text padding="10px 2px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="
              font-size: 16px;
              line-height: 1.5;
            ">Every successful company has a turning point—a risk that paid off, a product that redefined an industry, or a decision that changed everything. However, not every story is one of triumph; some of the most valuable lessons come from the failures and missteps that shaped the business landscape.</p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-divider border-width="1px" border-style="solid" border-color="lightgrey" padding="0px 0px" />
      </mj-column>
    </mj-section>
    
    <mj-spacer height="10px"></mj-spacer>

    <!-- Bussiness history -->
    <mj-section css-class="mj_fsection" background-color="#ffffff" css-class="mj_fsection">
      <mj-column background-color="#ffffff" width="100%">
        <mj-text padding="2px 12px 0px 12px" font-family="TNYAdobeCaslonPro, 'Times New Roman', serif;" color="white">
          <h2 style="
          padding-top:14px;
          color:#8C3321;
            text-align: left;
            border-bottom:2px solid #8C3321;
              font-size: 26px;
              line-height: 1.2;
              font-weight: 400;
              padding-bottom:8px;
            ">Caves, codes, and cloud: The Iron Mountain story</h2> 
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
    </mj-section>

    <!-- Content sections -->
    <mj-section background-color="#ffffff">
      <mj-column>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="TNYAdobeCaslonPro, 'Times New Roman', serif;" color="#000000">
          <h2 style="
              font-size: 24px;
              line-height: 1.2;
              font-weight: 400;
              margin-top: 2px !important;
            ">Fungi to files</h2>  
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">Iron Mountain didn’t begin as a high-security storage facility, but as a mushroom cultivation farm. In 1936, a German-American entrepreneur, <strong>Herman Knaust, bought a depleted iron ore mine in Kingston, New York, for $9,000</strong>. Herman Knaust and his brother Henry launched Knaust Brothers Inc., and at one point, they were the world’s largest mushroom growers and canners. Herman was even nicknamed the “Mushroom King of America.”
          </p>
        </mj-text>

        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px 14px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.businesshistory.co/email/images/vintage-truck-knausts-cavern-mushrooms-mine.png" alt="A vintage truck of Knausts Cavern Mushrooms stands before their mine" href="https://www.businesshistory.co" />
         <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;">
            <i>A vintage truck of "Knaust's Cavern Mushrooms" stands before their mine. Credits: Iron Mountain</i>
          </p>
        </mj-text>

        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5;filter:blur(5px);">However, as global mushroom markets expanded, cheaper European and Asian imports rolled in, and the fungi empire declined. By 1950, the mushroom market shifted, and Knaust searched for alternative uses for his mine, which he had already named “Iron Mountain.” Ever the opportunist and a master of adaptation, <strong>Herman Knaust noticed the growing Cold War paranoia and rising concerns about data security</strong>. So, he boldly rebranded the site as a bomb-resistant storage facility.
          </p>
          
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column> 
    </mj-section>
    <mj-spacer height="15px"></mj-spacer>
  </mj-body>
</mjml>